{{Infobox scientist | name = Boris Levitan | image = LEVITAN-B-M.jpg | image_size = 200px | caption = 1996 | birth_date = {{birth date|1914|06|07|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Berdyansk]], [[Russian Empire]] (present-day [[Ukraine]]) | death_date = {{death date and age|2004|04|04|1914|06|07|df=y}} | death_place = [[Minneapolis]], United States | fields = [[Mathematics]] | alma_mater = [[Kharkov State University]] | doctoral_advisor = [[Naum Akhiezer]] | doctoral_students = [[Grigory Isaakovich Barenblatt]] | known_for = [[Gelfand&ndash;Levitan equation]], [[Levitan almost-periodic functions]] | awards = [[Order of Lenin]] }} '''Boris Levitan''' (7 June 1914 &ndash; 4 April 2004) was a [[mathematician]] known in particular for his work on [[almost periodic functions]], and [[Sturm&ndash;Liouville operator]]s, especially, on [[inverse scattering transform|inverse scattering]].<ref>[http://www.startribune.com/stories/466/4716721.html Obituary in the [[Minneapolis Star Tribune]]] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040428225642/http://www.startribune.com/stories/466/4716721.html |date=April 28, 2004 }}</ref>
==Life==
Boris Levitan was born in [[Berdyansk]] (now south-eastern [[Ukraine]]), and grew up in [[Kharkov]]. He graduated from [[Kharkov University]] in 1936; in 1938, he submitted his PhD thesis "''Some Generalization of Almost Periodic Function''" under the supervision of [[Naum Akhiezer]].<ref>[http://genealogy.math.ndsu.nodak.edu/id.php?id=99630 Math Genealogy page]</ref> Then he defended the habilitation thesis "''Theory of Generalized Translation Operators''".
He was drafted into the army at the beginning of [[World War II]] in 1941, and served until 1944.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Kostyuchenko|first=A.G.|last2=Maslov|first2=V.P.|last3=Sadovnichii|first3=V.A.|last4=Sargsyan|first4=I.S.|last5=Shkalikov|first5=A.A.|last6=Zhikov|first6=V.V.|title=In memory of Boris Levitan.|journal=Russ. J. Math. Phys.|year=2006|volume=13|issue=1|pages=1&ndash;3}}</ref> From 1944 to 1961 he worked at the [[Soviet military academies#Felix Dzerzhinsky Military Rocket Forces Academy|Dzerzhinsky Military Academy]], and from 1961 in [[Moscow University]]. During the last years of his life, he worked in the [[University of Minnesota]].
