{{lowercase title}} In algebra, a '''j-multiplicity''' is a generalization of a [[Hilbert–Samuel multiplicity]]. For ''m''-primary ideals, the two notions coincide.<!-- It was introduced by Achilles and Manaresi in 1993, and has an application to the study of singularities in algebraic varieties.-->
== Definition == Let <math>(R, \mathfrak{m})</math> be a [[local ring|local]] [[Noetherian ring]] of [[Krull dimension]] <math>d > 0</math>. Then the '''j-multiplicity''' of an [[ideal (ring theory)|ideal]] ''I'' is :<math>j(I) = j(\operatorname{gr}_I R)</math> where <math>j(\operatorname{gr}_I R)</math> is the normalized coefficient of the degree ''d''&nbsp;&minus;&nbsp;1 term in the Hilbert polynomial <math>\Gamma_\mathfrak{m}(\operatorname{gr}_I R)</math>; <math>\Gamma_\mathfrak{m}</math> means the space of sections supported at <math>\mathfrak{m}</math>.
== References == *Daniel Katz, Javid Validashti, [http://www.math.ku.edu/~dlk/dkjv_final.pdf Multiplicities and Rees valuations] * {{cite journal | last1=Katz | first1=Daniel | last2=Validashti | first2=Javid | title=Multiplicities and Rees valuations | zbl=1216.13016 | journal=Collectanea Mathematica | volume=61 | pages=1–24 | year=2010 | doi=10.1007/BF03191222 | url=http://www.collectanea.ub.edu/index.php/Collectanea/article/viewArticle/5243 }}
